Set the color used when rendering. 

After calling `color()` all subsequent rendering will use the specified color
value. Color values must be in the range 0.0 to 1.0.  There a number of
different ways this function can be called. See the [examples](#examples)
section below for usage.

### syntax

~~~ python
color(grey)
color(r, g, b)
color(r, g, b, a)
color([r, g, b])
color([r, g, b, a])
~~~

### paramaters

grey | grey-scale value
r    | red value
g    | green value
b    | blue value
a    | alpha (transparency) value

### examples

#### set color with grey-scale value


<%= vroom_example_image "core", "color", "set-color-with-grey-scale-value.png" %>


~~~ python
def display():
   lighting(False)

   translateX(-5)
   color(0.1)
   cube(3.0)

   translateX(5)
   color(0.5)
   cube(3.0)

   translateX(5)
   color(0.9)
   cube(3.0)
~~~

#### set color using rgb values


<%= vroom_example_image "core", "color", "set-color-using-rgb-values.png" %>


~~~ python
def display():
   lighting(False)
   color(0.0, 1.0, 1.0)
   cube(3.0)
~~~

#### set color using rgb list


<%= vroom_example_image "core", "color", "set-color-using-rgb-list.png" %>


~~~ python
def display():
   lighting(False)
   color([1.0, 1.0, 0.0])
   cube(3.0)
~~~

#### set color using variable


<%= vroom_example_image "core", "color", "set-color-using-variable.png" %>


~~~ python
def display():
   lighting(False)
   my_color = [1.0, 0.0, 1.0]
   color(my_color)
   cube(3.0)
~~~

#### set color using alias


<%= vroom_example_image "core", "color", "set-color-using-alias.png" %>


~~~ python
def display():
   lighting(False)
   color(blue)
   cube(3.0)
~~~

